# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: insch-war-memorial-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The symptoms of COVID‑19 can vary but often include fever, fatigue, cough, breathing difficulties, loss of smell, and loss of taste.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Symptoms may begin one to fourteen days after exposure to the virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] At least a third of people who are infected do not develop noticeable symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Older people have a higher risk of developing severe symptoms and dying.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Some people experience persistent symptoms (long COVID), for months or years after infection, including fatigue, cognitive issues and shortness of breath.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Damage to organs has been observed in a subset.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID‑19 transmission occurs when infectious particles are breathed in or come into contact with the eyes, nose, or mouth.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The risk is highest when people are in close proximity, but small airborne particles containing the virus can remain suspended in the air and travel over longer distances, particularly indoors.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Transmission can also occur when people touch their eyes, nose, or mouth after touching surfaces or objects that have been contaminated by the virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] People remain contagious for up to 20 days and can spread the virus even if they do not develop symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] There are two common tests to detect a COVID infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Antigen tests (also called rapid lateral flow tests) can be used at home.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A positive test indicates an active infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] However, negative test results are not always accurate, especially when there are no symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Health care providers can perform a more accurate PCR test, which is typically analysed in a laboratory.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Several COVID-19 vaccines have been approved and distributed in various countries, many of which have initiated mass vaccination campaigns.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Other preventive measures include physical or social distancing, quarantining, ventilation of indoor spaces, use of face masks or coverings in public, covering coughs and sneezes, hand washing, and keeping unwashed hands away from the face.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Initial treatment consists of drugs that have been developed to inhibit the virus for those at high risk and symptomatic treatment, managing the disease through supportive care.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The first known case was identified in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Most scientists believe that the SARS-CoV-2 virus entered into human populations through natural zoonosis, similar to the SARS-CoV-1 and MERS-CoV outbreaks, and consistent with other pandemics in human history.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Social and environmental factors including climate change, natural ecosystem destruction and wildlife trade increased the likelihood of such zoonotic spillover.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] During the initial outbreak in Wuhan, the virus was commonly called "coronavirus" and "Wuhan coronavirus", and the disease was referred to by the same terms and sometimes as "Wuhan pneumonia".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In the past, many diseases have been named after geographical locations, such as the Spanish flu, Middle East respiratory syndrome, and Zika virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The official names COVID‑19 and SARS-CoV-2 were issued by the WHO on 11 February 2020 with COVID-19 being shorthand for "coronavirus disease 2019".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The WHO additionally uses "the COVID‑19 virus" and "the virus responsible for COVID‑19" in public communications.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The symptoms of COVID-19 are variable depending on the type of variant contracted, ranging from mild symptoms to a potentially fatal illness.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Common symptoms include coughing, fever, loss of smell and taste, with less common ones including headaches, nasal congestion and runny nose, muscle pain, sore throat, diarrhea, eye irritation, and toes swelling or turning purple, and in moderate to severe cases, breathing difficulties.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] People with the COVID-19 infection may have different symptoms, and their symptoms may change over time.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In people without prior ear, nose, or throat disorders, loss of taste combined with loss of smell is associated with COVID-19 and is reported in as many as 88% of symptomatic cases.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] At least a third of the people who are infected with the virus do not develop noticeable symptoms at any point in time.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] These asymptomatic carriers tend not to get tested and can still spread the disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Other infected people will develop symptoms later (called "pre-symptomatic") or have very mild symptoms and can also spread the virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] As is common with infections, there is a delay, or incubation period, between the moment a person first becomes infected and the appearance of the first symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The median delay for COVID-19 is four to five days possibly being infectious on 1–4 of those days.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Most symptomatic people experience symptoms within two to seven days after exposure, and almost all will experience at least one symptom within 12 days.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Most people recover from the acute phase of the disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] However, some people continue to experience a range of effects, such as fatigue, for prolonged periods after an initial COVID-19 infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] This is the result of a condition called long COVID, which can be described as a range of persistent symptoms that continue for months or years.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Long-term damage to organs has been observed after the onset of COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Multi-year studies are underway to further investigate the protracted effects of long COVID.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Reducing the risk of long COVID includes staying up to date on the most recent COVID-19 vaccine, practicing good hygiene, maintaining clean indoor air, and physical distancing from people infected with a respiratory virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Omicron variant became dominant in the U.S. in December 2021.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Symptoms with the Omicron variant are less severe than they are with other variants.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Complications may include pneumonia, acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), multi-organ failure, septic shock, and death.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Cardiovascular complications may include heart failure, arrhythmias (including atrial fibrillation), heart inflammation, thrombosis, particularly venous thromboembolism, and endothelial cell injury and dysfunction.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Approximately 20–30% of people who present with COVID‑19 have elevated liver enzymes, reflecting liver injury.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Neurologic manifestations include seizure, stroke, encephalitis, and Guillain–Barré syndrome (which includes loss of motor functions).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Following the infection, children may develop paediatric multisystem inflammatory syndrome, which has symptoms similar to Kawasaki disease, which can be fatal.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In very rare cases, acute encephalopathy can occur, and it can be considered in those who have been diagnosed with COVID‑19 and have an altered mental status.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] According to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, pregnant women are at increased risk of becoming seriously ill from COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] This is because pregnant women with COVID‑19 appear to be more likely to develop respiratory and obstetric complications that can lead to miscarriage, premature delivery and intrauterine growth restriction.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Fungal infections such as aspergillosis, candidiasis, cryptococcosis and mucormycosis have been recorded in people recovering from COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID‑19 is caused by infection with a coronavirus known as "severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2" (SARS-CoV-2).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID-19 is mainly transmitted from person to person through inhaling air contaminated by droplets/aerosols and small airborne particles containing the virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Infected people exhale those particles as they breathe, talk, cough, sneeze, or sing.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Transmission is most likely at closer range but can also occur over longer distances, particularly indoors.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus spreads through virus-laden fluid particles, or droplets, which are created in the respiratory tract, and they are expelled by the mouth and the nose.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] There are three types of transmission: "droplet" and "contact", which are associated with large droplets, and "airborne", which is associated with small droplets.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] If the droplets are above a certain critical size, they settle faster than they evaporate, and therefore they contaminate surfaces surrounding them.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Droplets that are below a certain critical size, generally thought to be <100μm diameter, evaporate faster than they settle; due to that fact, they form respiratory aerosol particles that remain airborne for a long period of time over extensive distances.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Infectivity can begin four to five days before the onset of symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Infected people can spread the disease even if they are pre-symptomatic or asymptomatic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Most commonly, the peak viral load in upper respiratory tract samples occurs close to the time of symptom onset and declines after the first week after symptoms begin.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Current evidence suggests a duration of viral shedding and the period of infectiousness of up to ten days following symptom onset for people with mild to moderate COVID-19, and up to 20 days for persons with severe COVID-19, including immunocompromised people.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Infectious particles range in size from aerosols that remain suspended in the air for long periods of time to larger droplets that remain airborne briefly or fall to the ground.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Additionally, COVID-19 research has redefined the traditional understanding of how respiratory viruses are transmitted.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The largest droplets of respiratory fluid do not travel far, but can be inhaled or land on mucous membranes on the eyes, nose, or mouth to infect.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) is a novel severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It was first isolated from three people with pneumonia connected to the cluster of acute respiratory illness cases in Wuhan.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] All structural features of the novel SARS-CoV-2 virus particle occur in related coronaviruses in nature, particularly in *Rhinolophus sinicus* (Chinese horseshoe bats).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Outside the human body, the virus is destroyed by household soap which bursts its protective bubble.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Hospital disinfectants, alcohols, heat, povidone-iodine, and ultraviolet-C (UV-C) irradiation are also effective disinfection methods for surfaces.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] SARS-CoV-2 is closely related to the original SARS-CoV.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is thought to have an animal (zoonotic) origin.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Genetic analysis has revealed that the coronavirus genetically clusters with the genus *Betacoronavirus*, in subgenus *Sarbecovirus* (lineage B) together with two bat-derived strains.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is 96% identical at the whole genome level to other bat coronavirus samples (BatCov RaTG13).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The structural proteins of SARS-CoV-2 include membrane glycoprotein (M), envelope protein (E), nucleocapsid protein (N), and the spike protein (S).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The M protein of SARS-CoV-2 is about 98% similar to the M protein of bat SARS-CoV, maintains around 98% homology with pangolin SARS-CoV, and has 90% homology with the M protein of SARS-CoV; whereas, the similarity is only around 38% with the M protein of MERS-CoV.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The SARS-CoV-2 virus that causes COVID-19 has continuously evolved since the start of the pandemic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Once a large number of mutations have accumulated, a subtype is classified as a variant.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Major variants of concern were given a name based on letters of the Greek alphabet, for example, Alpha, Beta, Delta; after naming the Omicron variant in November 2021, the WHO stopped naming new variants of concern.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Pango system further specifies the lineage of the variant, for instance, JN.1 for a variant active in 2024, and XFG for one in 2025.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Alpha variant (B.1.1.7) first appeared around autumn 2020.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] By the end of 2020, two other variants of concern had appeared: Gamma (P.1), which was first seen in Brazil and Beta (B.1.351), which was first detected in South Africa.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Alpha came to dominate the Northern Hemisphere, Gamma in South America and Beta in Africa.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Delta variant (B.1.617.2) was first seen in India around the same time, and came to dominate globally in 2021.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Omicron variant which emerged at the end of 2021, saw a large number of mutations compared to previous variants and has been dominant since.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] New variants can quickly come to dominate global transmission when they have an advantage compared to previous variants.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Within the span of about 7 weeks, the Omicron variant went from 1% of global cases to 95% by January 2022.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In addition to differences in how well the virus is transmitted, the variants differ in how well they evade vaccine protection, their severity and the risk of different long COVID symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Omicron variant seems to have decreased severity compared to previous strains, but was better able to evade the original vaccines.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The SARS-CoV-2 virus can infect a wide range of cells and systems of the body.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID‑19 is most known for affecting the upper respiratory tract (sinuses, nose, and throat) and the lower respiratory tract (windpipe and lungs).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The lungs are the organs most affected by COVID‑19 because the virus accesses host cells via the receptor for the enzyme angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2), which is most abundant on the surface of type II alveolar cells of the lungs.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus uses a special surface glycoprotein called a "spike" to connect to the ACE2 receptor and enter the host cell.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Following viral entry, COVID‑19 infects the ciliated epithelium of the nasopharynx and upper airways.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Autopsies of people who died of COVID‑19 have found diffuse alveolar damage, and lymphocyte-containing inflammatory infiltrates within the lung.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] From the CT scans of COVID-19 infected lungs, white patches were observed containing fluid known as ground-glass opacity (GGO) or simply ground glass.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] This tended to correlate with the clear jelly liquid found in lung autopsies of people who died of COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] One possibility addressed in medical research is that hyuralonic acid (HA) could be the leading factor for this observation of the clear jelly liquid found in the lungs, in what could be hyuralonic storm, in conjunction with cytokine storm.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] One common symptom, loss of smell, results from infection of the support cells of the olfactory epithelium, with subsequent damage to the olfactory neurons.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The involvement of both the central and peripheral nervous system in COVID‑19 has been reported in many medical publications.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is clear that many people with COVID-19 exhibit neurological or mental health issues.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus is not detected in the central nervous system (CNS) of the majority of people with COVID-19 who also have neurological issues.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] However, SARS-CoV-2 has been detected at low levels in the brains of those who have died from COVID‑19, but these results need to be confirmed.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] While virus has been detected in cerebrospinal fluid of autopsies, the exact mechanism by which it invades the CNS remains unclear and may first involve invasion of peripheral nerves given the low levels of ACE2 in the brain.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus may also enter the bloodstream from the lungs and cross the blood–brain barrier to gain access to the CNS, possibly within an infected white blood cell.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Research conducted when Alpha was the dominant variant has suggested COVID-19 may cause brain damage.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Later research showed that all variants studied (including Omicron) killed brain cells, but the exact cells killed varied by variant.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is unknown if such damage is temporary or permanent.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] All effects were more pronounced among older ages.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus also affects gastrointestinal organs as ACE2 is abundantly expressed in the glandular cells of gastric, duodenal and rectal epithelium as well as endothelial cells and enterocytes of the small intestine.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus can cause acute myocardial injury and chronic damage to the cardiovascular system.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] An acute cardiac injury was found in 12% of infected people admitted to the hospital in Wuhan, China, and is more frequent in severe disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Rates of cardiovascular symptoms are high, owing to the systemic inflammatory response and immune system disorders during disease progression, but acute myocardial injuries may also be related to ACE2 receptors in the heart.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] ACE2 receptors are highly expressed in the heart and are involved in heart function.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A high incidence of thrombosis and venous thromboembolism occurs in people transferred to intensive care units with COVID‑19 infections, and may be related to poor prognosis.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Infection may initiate a chain of vasoconstrictive responses within the body, including pulmonary vasoconstriction – a possible mechanism in which oxygenation decreases during pneumonia.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Furthermore, damage of arterioles and capillaries was found in brain tissue samples of people who died from COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID‑19 may also cause substantial structural changes to blood cells, sometimes persisting for months after hospital discharge.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A low level of blood lymphocytess may result from the virus acting through ACE2-related entry into lymphocytes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Another common cause of death is complications related to the kidneys.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Early reports show that up to 30% of people hospitalised with COVID-19 both in China and in New York have experienced some injury to their kidneys, including some persons with no previous kidney problems.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Although SARS-CoV-2 has a tropism for ACE2-expressing epithelial cells of the respiratory tract, people with severe COVID‑19 have symptoms of systemic hyperinflammation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Interferon alpha plays a complex, Janus-faced role in the pathogenesis of COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Although it promotes the elimination of virus-infected cells, it also upregulates the expression of ACE-2, thereby facilitating the SARS-Cov2 virus to enter cells and to replicate.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A competition of negative feedback loops (via protective effects of interferon alpha) and positive feedback loops (via upregulation of ACE-2) is assumed to determine the fate of people with COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Additionally, people with COVID‑19 and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) have classical serum biomarkers of CRS, including elevated C-reactive protein (CRP), lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), D-dimer, and ferritin.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Systemic inflammation results in vasodilation, allowing inflammatory lymphocytic and monocytic infiltration of the lung and the heart.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In particular, pathogenic GM-CSF-secreting T cells were shown to correlate with the recruitment of inflammatory IL-6-secreting monocytes and severe lung pathology in people with COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Lymphocytic infiltrates have also been reported at autopsy.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Multiple viral and host factors affect the pathogenesis of the virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The S-protein, otherwise known as the spike protein, is the viral component that attaches to the host receptor via the ACE2 receptors.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Studies have shown that S1 domain induced IgG and IgA antibody levels at a much higher capacity.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is the focus spike proteins expression that are involved in many effective COVID‑19 vaccines.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The M protein is the viral protein responsible for the transmembrane transport of nutrients.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is the cause of the bud release and the formation of the viral envelope.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The N and E protein are accessory proteins that interfere with the host's immune response.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Human angiotensin converting enzyme 2 (hACE2) is the host factor that SARS-CoV-2 virus targets causing COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Theoretically, the usage of angiotensin receptor blockers (ARB) and ACE inhibitors upregulating ACE2 expression might increase morbidity with COVID‑19, though animal data suggest some potential protective effect of ARB; however no clinical studies have proven susceptibility or outcomes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Until further data is available, guidelines and recommendations for people with hypertension remain.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The effect of the virus on ACE2 cell surfaces leads to leukocytic infiltration, increased blood vessel permeability, alveolar wall permeability, as well as decreased secretion of lung surfactants.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] These effects cause the majority of the respiratory symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] However, the aggravation of local inflammation causes a cytokine storm eventually leading to a systemic inflammatory response syndrome.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Among healthy adults not exposed to SARS-CoV-2, about 35% have CD4+ T cells that recognise the SARS-CoV-2 S protein (particularly the S2 subunit) and about 50% react to other proteins of the virus, suggesting cross-reactivity from previous common colds caused by other coronaviruses.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It is unknown whether different persons use similar antibody genes in response to COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The severity of the inflammation can be attributed to the severity of what is known as the cytokine storm.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Levels of interleukin 1B, interferon-gamma, interferon-inducible protein 10, and monocyte chemoattractant protein 1 were all associated with COVID‑19 disease severity.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Treatment has been proposed to combat the cytokine storm as it remains to be one of the leading causes of morbidity and mortality in COVID‑19 disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A cytokine storm is due to an acute hyperinflammatory response that is responsible for clinical illness in an array of diseases but in COVID‑19, it is related to worse prognosis and increased fatality.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The storm causes acute respiratory distress syndrome, blood clotting events such as strokes, myocardial infarction, encephalitis, acute kidney injury, and vasculitis.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The production of IL-1, IL-2, IL-6, TNF-alpha, and interferon-gamma, all crucial components of normal immune responses, inadvertently become the causes of a cytokine storm.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The cells of the central nervous system, the microglia, neurons, and astrocytes, are also involved in the release of pro-inflammatory cytokines affecting the nervous system, and effects of cytokine storms toward the CNS are not uncommon.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Interestingly patients with obesity, who tend to develop more severe disease, demonstrate reduced inflammatory responses in their lungs.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] This was most marked in the type I interferon responses and TNF-alpha, although notably the TNF response was not attenuated in the blood.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The supposition is that the reduced pulmonary anti-viral defences leads to increase viral proliferation and greater damage, leading to more severe respiratory failure.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] There are many unknowns for pregnant women during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Given that they are prone to have complications and severe disease infection with other types of coronaviruses, they have been identified as a vulnerable group and advised to take supplementary preventive measures.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] However, from the evidence base, it is difficult to conclude whether pregnant women are at increased risk of grave consequences of this virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In addition to the above, other clinical studies have proved that SARS-CoV-2 can affect the period of pregnancy in different ways.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] On the one hand, there is little evidence of its impact up to 12 weeks gestation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] On the other hand, COVID-19 infection may cause increased rates of unfavourable outcomes in the course of the pregnancy.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Some examples of these could be foetal growth restriction, preterm birth, and perinatal mortality, which refers to the foetal death past 22 or 28 completed weeks of pregnancy as well as the death among live-born children up to seven completed days of life.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] For preterm birth, a 2023 review indicates that there appears to be a correlation with COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Unvaccinated women in later stages of pregnancy with COVID-19 are more likely than other people to need very intensive care.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Babies born to mothers with COVID-19 are more likely to have breathing problems.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Pregnant women are strongly encouraged to get vaccinated.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID‑19 can provisionally be diagnosed on the basis of symptoms and confirmed using reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) or other nucleic acid testing of infected secretions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Along with laboratory testing, chest CT scans may be helpful to diagnose COVID‑19 in individuals with a high clinical suspicion of infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Detection of a past infection is possible with serological tests, which detect antibodies produced by the body in response to the infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The standard methods of testing for presence of SARS-CoV-2 are nucleic acid tests, which detects the presence of viral RNA fragments.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] As these tests detect RNA but not infectious virus, its "ability to determine duration of infectivity of patients is limited".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The test is typically done on respiratory samples obtained by a nasopharyngeal swab; however, a nasal swab or sputum sample may also be used.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Results are generally available within hours.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Several laboratories and companies have developed serological tests, which detect antibodies produced by the body in response to infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Some have been evaluated by Public Health England and approved for use in the UK.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Chest CT scans may be helpful to diagnose COVID‑19 in individuals with a high clinical suspicion of infection but are not recommended for routine screening.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Bilateral multilobar ground-glass opacities with a peripheral, asymmetric, and posterior distribution are common in early infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Subpleural dominance, crazy paving (lobular septal thickening with variable alveolar filling), and consolidation may appear as the disease progresses.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Characteristic imaging features on chest radiographs and computed tomography (CT) of people who are symptomatic include asymmetric peripheral ground-glass opacities without pleural effusions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Many groups have created COVID‑19 datasets that include imagery such as the Italian Radiological Society which has compiled an international online database of imaging findings for confirmed cases.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Due to overlap with other infections such as adenovirus, imaging without confirmation by rRT-PCR is of limited specificity in identifying COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A large study in China compared chest CT results to PCR and demonstrated that though imaging is less specific for the infection, it is faster and more sensitive.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In late 2019, the WHO assigned emergency ICD-10 disease codes U07.1 for deaths from lab-confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection and U07.2 for deaths from clinically or epidemiologically diagnosed COVID‑19 without lab-confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The first COVID‑19 vaccine was granted regulatory approval on 2 December 2020 by the UK medicines regulator MHRA.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] It was evaluated for emergency use authorisation (EUA) status by the US FDA, and in several other countries.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Initially, the US National Institutes of Health guidelines do not recommend any medication for prevention of COVID‑19, before or after exposure to the SARS-CoV-2 virus, outside the setting of a clinical trial.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Without a vaccine, other prophylactic measures, or effective treatments, a key part of managing COVID‑19 is trying to decrease and delay the epidemic peak, known as "flattening the curve".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] This is done by slowing the infection rate to decrease the risk of health services being overwhelmed, allowing for better treatment of active cases, and delaying additional cases until effective treatments or a vaccine become available.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Major vaccines include the Pfizer–BioNTech mRNA vaccine, Moderna mRNA vaccine, and the Novavax protein subunit vaccine.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] With the emergence of new SARS-CoV-2 variants, the original vaccines—particularly Pfizer–BioNTech and Moderna vaccines—have been updated.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] These "variant-adapted" vaccines are offered as booster doses.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The immunity from the vaccines also wanes over time, requiring people to get boosters to maintain protection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Common side effects of COVID‑19 vaccines include soreness, fatigue, headache, myalgia (muscle pain), and arthralgia (joint pain), which resolve without medical treatment within a few days.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] COVID‑19 vaccination is safe for people who are pregnant or are breastfeeding.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The COVID‑19 vaccines are widely credited for their role in reducing the spread of COVID‑19 and reducing the severity and death caused by COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The Australian-based medical journal *Journal of Paediatrics and Child Health* estimated that between 14.4 and 19.8 million deaths were prevented by the vaccine.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Many countries implemented phased distribution plans that prioritized those at highest risk of complications, such as the elderly, and those at high risk of exposure, such as healthcare workers.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] By December 2020, more than 10 billion vaccine doses had been preordered, with about half of the doses purchased by high-income countries comprising 14% of the world's population.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] As of August 2024, over 13 billion doses of COVID‑19 vaccines have been administered worldwide.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In community and healthcare settings, the use of face masks was intended as source control to limit transmission of the virus and for personal protection to prevent infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] When properly worn, face masks can limit the respiratory droplets and aerosols that are spread by infected individuals, helping protect healthy individuals from infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Scientific studies have concluded that the use of face masks is effective in protecting the individual using them against COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Various case-control and population-based studies have also shown that the increased use of masks in a community reduces the spread of SARS-CoV-2, although there is a paucity of evidence from randomized controlled trials (RCTs).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Fitted N95s outperform surgical masks, while cloth masks provide marginal protection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] During the public health emergency, governments widely recommended (and, in some jurisdictions, mandated) the wearing of masks.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Prominent national and intergovernmental health agencies and their leaders recommended the use of masks to reduce transmission, including the WHO, American, European, and Chinese Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The CDC states that avoiding crowded indoor spaces reduces the risk of COVID-19 infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] When indoors, increasing the rate of air change, decreasing recirculation of air and increasing the use of outdoor air can reduce transmission.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The WHO recommends ventilation and air filtration in public spaces to help clear out infectious aerosols.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Exhaled respiratory particles can build-up within enclosed spaces with inadequate ventilation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The risk of COVID‑19 infection increases especially in spaces where people engage in physical exertion or raise their voice (e.g., exercising, shouting, singing) as this increases exhalation of respiratory droplets.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Prolonged exposure to these conditions, typically more than 15 minutes, leads to higher risk of infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Displacement ventilation with large natural inlets can move stale air directly to the exhaust in laminar flow while significantly reducing the concentration of droplets and particles.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Passive ventilation reduces energy consumption and maintenance costs but may lack controllability and heat recovery.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Displacement ventilation can also be achieved mechanically with higher energy and maintenance costs.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The use of large ducts and openings helps to prevent mixing in closed environments.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Recirculation and mixing should be avoided because recirculation prevents dilution of harmful particles and redistributes possibly contaminated air, and mixing increases the concentration and range of infectious particles and keeps larger particles in the air.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Thorough hand hygiene after any cough or sneeze is required.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The WHO also recommends that individuals wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds, especially after going to the toilet or when hands are visibly dirty, before eating and after blowing one's nose.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] When soap and water are not available, the CDC recommends using an alcohol-based hand sanitiser with at least 60% alcohol.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] For areas where commercial hand sanitisers are not readily available, the WHO provides two formulations for local production.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In these formulations, the antimicrobial activity arises from ethanol or isopropanol.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Hydrogen peroxide is used to help eliminate bacterial spores in the alcohol; it is "not an active substance for hand antisepsis".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Social distancing (also known as physical distancing) includes infection control actions intended to slow the spread of the disease by minimising close contact between individuals.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Methods include quarantines; travel restrictions; and the closing of schools, workplaces, stadiums, theatres, or shopping centres.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Individuals may apply social distancing methods by staying at home, limiting travel, avoiding crowded areas, using no-contact greetings, and physically distancing themselves from others.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In 2020, outbreaks occurred in prisons due to crowding and an inability to enforce adequate social distancing.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In the United States, the prisoner population is ageing and many of them are at high risk for poor outcomes from COVID‑19 due to high rates of coexisting heart and lung disease, and poor access to high-quality healthcare.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] After being expelled from the body, coronaviruses can survive on surfaces for hours to days.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] If a person touches the dirty surface, they may deposit the virus at the eyes, nose, or mouth where it can enter the body and cause infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Evidence indicates that contact with infected surfaces is not the main driver of COVID‑19, leading to recommendations for optimised disinfection procedures to avoid issues such as the increase of antimicrobial resistance through the use of inappropriate cleaning products and processes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Deep cleaning and other surface sanitation has been criticised as hygiene theatre, giving a false sense of security against something primarily spread through the air.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The amount of time that the virus can survive depends significantly on the type of surface, the temperature, and the humidity.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Coronaviruses die very quickly when exposed to the UV light in sunlight.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Like other enveloped viruses, SARS-CoV-2 survives longest when the temperature is at room temperature or lower, and when the relative humidity is low (<50%).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] On many surfaces, including glass, some types of plastic, stainless steel, and skin, the virus can remain infective for several days indoors at room temperature, or even about a week under ideal conditions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] On some surfaces, including cotton fabric and copper, the virus usually dies after a few hours.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The virus dies faster on porous surfaces than on non-porous surfaces due to capillary action within pores and faster aerosol droplet evaporation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] However, of the many surfaces tested, two with the longest survival times are N95 respirator masks and surgical masks, both of which are considered porous surfaces.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The CDC says that in most situations, cleaning surfaces with soap or detergent, not disinfecting, is enough to reduce risk of transmission.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Other solutions, such as benzalkonium chloride and chlorhexidine gluconate, are less effective.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Ultraviolet germicidal irradiation may also be used, although popular devices require 5–10 min exposure and may deteriorate some materials over time.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Self-isolation at home has been recommended for those diagnosed with COVID‑19 and those who suspect they have been infected.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Health agencies have issued detailed instructions for proper self-isolation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Many governments have mandated or recommended self-quarantine for entire populations.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The strongest self-quarantine instructions have been issued to those in high-risk groups.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Those who may have been exposed to someone with COVID‑19 and those who have recently travelled to a country or region with the widespread transmission have been advised to self-quarantine for 14 days from the time of last possible exposure.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] A 2021 Cochrane rapid review found that based upon low-certainty evidence, international travel-related control measures such as restricting cross-border travel may help to contain the spread of COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Additionally, symptom/exposure-based screening measures at borders may miss many positive cases.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] While test-based border screening measures may be more effective, it could also miss many positive cases if only conducted upon arrival without follow-up.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The review concluded that a minimum 10-day quarantine may be beneficial in preventing the spread of COVID‑19 and may be more effective if combined with an additional control measure like border screening.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] The treatment and management of COVID-19 combines both supportive care, which includes treatment to relieve symptoms, fluid therapy, oxygen support as needed, and a growing list of approved medications.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Highly effective vaccines have reduced mortality related to SARS-CoV-2; for those awaiting vaccination, as well as for the estimated millions of immunocompromised persons who are unlikely to respond robustly to vaccination, treatment remains important.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Some people may experience persistent symptoms or disability after recovery from the infection, known as long COVID, but there is still limited information on the best management and rehabilitation for this condition.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In these, supportive care includes medication such as paracetamol or NSAIDs to relieve symptoms (fever, body aches, cough), proper intake of fluids, rest, and nasal breathing.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Good personal hygiene and a healthy diet are also recommended.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommended that those who suspect they are carrying the virus isolate themselves at home and wear a face mask.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] As of November 2020 use of the glucocorticoid dexamethasone had been strongly recommended in those severe cases treated in hospital with low oxygen levels, to reduce the risk of death.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Noninvasive ventilation and, ultimately, admission to an intensive care unit for mechanical ventilation may be required to support breathing.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) has been used to address respiratory failure, but its benefits are still under consideration.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Some of the cases of severe disease course are caused by systemic hyper-inflammation, the so-called *cytokine storm*.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Although several medications have been approved in different countries as of April 2022, not all countries have these medications.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Patients with mild to moderate symptoms who are in the risk groups can take nirmatrelvir/ritonavir (marketed as Paxlovid) or remdesivir, either of which reduces the risk of serious illness or hospitalization.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In the US, the Biden Administration COVID-19 action plan includes the Test to Treat initiative, where people can go to a pharmacy, take a COVID test, and immediately receive free Paxlovid if they test positive.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] In November 2021, the UK approved the use of molnupiravir as a COVID treatment for vulnerable patients recently diagnosed with the disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p01] Several experimental treatments are being actively studied in clinical trials.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The disease may take a mild course with few or no symptoms, resembling other common upper respiratory diseases such as the common cold.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In 3–4% of cases (7.4% for those over age 65) symptoms are severe enough to cause hospitalisation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Mild cases typically recover within two weeks, while those with severe or critical diseases may take three to six weeks to recover.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Among those who have died, the time from symptom onset to death has ranged from two to eight weeks.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The Italian Istituto Superiore di Sanità reported that the median time between the onset of symptoms and death was twelve days, with seven being hospitalised.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] However, people transferred to an ICU had a median time of ten days between hospitalisation and death.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Abnormal sodium levels during hospitalisation with COVID-19 are associated with poor prognoses: high sodium with a greater risk of death, and low sodium with an increased chance of needing ventilator support.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Prolonged prothrombin time and elevated C-reactive protein levels on admission to the hospital are associated with severe course of COVID‑19 and with a transfer to ICU.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Some early studies suggest 10% to 20% of people with COVID‑19 will experience symptoms lasting longer than a month.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A majority of those who were admitted to hospital with severe disease report long-term problems including fatigue and shortness of breath.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 30 October 2020, WHO chief Tedros Adhanom warned that "to a significant number of people, the COVID virus poses a range of serious long-term effects".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] He has described the vast spectrum of COVID‑19 symptoms that fluctuate over time as "really concerning".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] They range from fatigue, a cough and shortness of breath, to inflammation and injury of major organs – including the lungs and heart, and also neurological and psychologic effects.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Symptoms often overlap and can affect any system in the body.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Infected people have reported cyclical bouts of fatigue, headaches, months of complete exhaustion, mood swings, and other symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Tedros therefore concluded that a strategy of achieving herd immunity by infection, rather than vaccination, is "morally unconscionable and unfeasible".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In terms of hospital readmissions about 9% of 106,000 individuals had to return for hospital treatment within two months of discharge.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The average to readmit was eight days since first hospital visit.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There are several risk factors that have been identified as being a cause of multiple admissions to a hospital facility.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Among these are advanced age (above 65 years of age) and presence of a chronic condition such as diabetes, COPD, heart failure or chronic kidney disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to scientific reviews smokers are more likely to require intensive care or die compared to non-smokers.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Acting on the same ACE2 pulmonary receptors affected by smoking, air pollution has been correlated with the disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Short-term and chronic exposure to air pollution seems to enhance morbidity and mortality from COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Pre-existing heart and lung diseases and also obesity, especially in conjunction with fatty liver disease, contributes to an increased health risk of COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] It is also assumed that those that are immunocompromised are at higher risk of getting severely sick from SARS-CoV-2.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] One research study that looked into the COVID‑19 infections in hospitalised kidney transplant recipients found a mortality rate of 11%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Men with untreated hypogonadism were 2.4 times more likely than men with eugonadism to be hospitalised if they contracted COVID-19; Hypogonad men treated with testosterone were less likely to be hospitalised for COVID-19 than men who were not treated for hypogonadism.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Genetics plays an important role in the ability to fight off Covid.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] For instance, those that do not produce detectable type I interferons or produce auto-antibodies against these may get much sicker from COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Genetic screening is able to detect interferon effector genes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Some genetic variants are risk factors in specific populations.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] For instance, an allele of the DOCK2 gene (dedicator of cytokinesis 2 gene) is a common risk factor in Asian populations but much less common in Europe.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The mutation leads to lower expression of DOCK2 especially in younger people with severe COVID-19 infections.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In fact, many other genes and genetic variants have been found that determine the outcome of SARS-CoV-2 infections.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A series of studies have examined a potential relationship between blood group and COVID-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Initial research conducted by scientists in Wuhan, China, on thousands of infected patients suggested that individuals with blood group A were more likely to experience severe symptoms of COVID-19 infection compared to those with blood group O.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Other blood types fell between these two in terms of relative risk.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A second study, published in the *New England Journal of Medicine*, did not establish a causal relationship between blood type and the severity of COVID-19, but it did support the earlier findings from Chinese researchers.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] However, later studies conducted in other countries did not confirm a significant or meaningful link between blood type and disease severity, calling into question the universality of the initial findings.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] While very young children have experienced lower rates of infection, older children have a rate of infection that is similar to the population as a whole.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Children are likely to have milder symptoms and are at lower risk of severe disease than adults.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The CDC reports that in the US roughly a third of hospitalised children were admitted to the ICU, while a European multinational study of hospitalised children from June 2020, found that about 8% of children admitted to a hospital needed intensive care.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Four of the 582 children (0.7%) in the European study died, but the actual mortality rate may be "substantially lower" since milder cases that did not seek medical help were not included in the study.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Around 10% to 30% of non-hospitalised people with COVID-19 go on to develop long COVID.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] For those that do need hospitalisation, the incidence of long-term effects is over 50%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Long COVID is an often severe multisystem disease with a large set of symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Common symptoms are fatigue, post-exertional malaise, cognitive issues, shortness of breath and pain.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There are likely various, possibly coinciding, causes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Organ damage from the acute infection can explain a part of the symptoms, but long COVID is also observed in people where organ damage seems to be absent.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] By a variety of mechanisms, the lungs are the organs most affected in COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In people requiring hospital admission, up to 98% of CT scans performed show lung abnormalities after 28 days of illness even if they had clinically improved.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] People with advanced age, severe disease, prolonged ICU stays, or who smoke are more likely to have long-lasting effects, including pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Overall, approximately one-third of those investigated after four weeks will have findings of pulmonary fibrosis or reduced lung function as measured by DLCO, even in asymptomatic people, but with the suggestion of continuing improvement with the passing of more time.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] After severe disease, lung function can take anywhere from three months to a year or more to return to previous levels.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The risks of cognitive deficit, dementia, psychotic disorders, and epilepsy or seizures persists at an increased level two years after infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The immune response by humans to SARS-CoV-2 virus occurs as a combination of the cell-mediated immunity and antibody production, just as with most other infections.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] B cells interact with T cells and begin dividing before selection into the plasma cell, partly on the basis of their affinity for antigen.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Since SARS-CoV-2 has been in the human population only since December 2019, it remains unknown if the immunity is long-lasting in people who recover from the disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The presence of neutralising antibodies in blood strongly correlates with protection from infection, but the level of neutralising antibody declines with time.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Those with asymptomatic or mild disease had undetectable levels of neutralising antibody two months after infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In another study, the level of neutralising antibodies fell four-fold one to four months after the onset of symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] However, the lack of antibodies in the blood does not mean antibodies will not be rapidly produced upon reexposure to SARS-CoV-2.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Memory B cells specific for the spike and nucleocapsid proteins of SARS-CoV-2 last for at least six months after the appearance of symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] As of August 2021, reinfection with COVID‑19 was possible but uncommon.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The first case of reinfection was documented in August 2020.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A systematic review found 17 cases of confirmed reinfection in medical literature as of May 2021.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] With the Omicron variant, as of 2022, reinfections have become common, albeit it is unclear how common.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] COVID-19 reinfections are thought to likely be less severe than primary infections, especially if one was previously infected by the same variant.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Several measures are commonly used to quantify mortality.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] These numbers vary by region and over time and are influenced by the volume of testing, healthcare system quality, treatment options, time since the initial outbreak, and population characteristics such as age, sex, and overall health.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The mortality rate reflects the number of deaths within a specific demographic group divided by the population of that demographic group.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Consequently, the mortality rate reflects the prevalence as well as the severity of the disease within a given population.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Mortality rates are highly correlated to age, with relatively low rates for young people and relatively high rates among the elderly.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In fact, one relevant factor of mortality rates is the age structure of the countries' populations.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] For example, the case fatality rate for COVID‑19 is lower in India than in the US since India's younger population represents a larger percentage than in the US.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The case fatality rate (CFR) reflects the number of deaths divided by the number of diagnosed cases within a given time interval.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A key metric in gauging the severity of COVID‑19 is the infection fatality rate (IFR), also referred to as the *infection fatality ratio* or *infection fatality risk*.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] This metric is calculated by dividing the total number of deaths from the disease by the total number of infected individuals; hence, in contrast to the CFR, the IFR incorporates asymptomatic and undiagnosed infections as well as reported cases.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] These results were also highlighted in a December 2020 report issued by the WHO.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] At an early stage of the pandemic, the World Health Organization reported estimates of IFR between 0.3% and 1%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 2 July, The WHO's chief scientist reported that the average IFR estimate presented at a two-day WHO expert forum was about 0.6%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In August, the WHO found that studies incorporating data from broad serology testing in Europe showed IFR estimates converging at approximately 0.5–1%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Firm lower limits of IFRs have been established in a number of locations such as New York City and Bergamo in Italy since the IFR cannot be less than the population fatality rate.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] (After sufficient time however, people can get reinfected).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] As of 10 July, in New York City, with a population of 8.4 million, 23,377 individuals (18,758 confirmed and 4,619 probable) have died with COVID‑19 (0.3% of the population).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Antibody testing in New York City suggested an IFR of ≈0.9%, and ≈1.4%.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In Bergamo province, 0.6% of the population has died.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported preliminary estimates of age-specific IFRs for public health planning purposes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] COVID‑19 case fatality rates are higher among men than women in most countries.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] However, in a few countries like India, Nepal, Vietnam, and Slovenia the fatality cases are higher in women than men.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Globally, men are more likely to be admitted to the ICU and more likely to die.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] One meta-analysis found that globally, men were more likely to get COVID‑19 than women; there were approximately 55 men and 45 women per 100 infections (CI: 51.43–56.58).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention reported the death rate was 2.8% for men and 1.7% for women.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Later reviews in June 2020 indicated that there is no significant difference in susceptibility or in CFR between genders.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] One review acknowledges the different mortality rates in Chinese men, suggesting that it may be attributable to lifestyle choices such as smoking and drinking alcohol rather than genetic factors.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Smoking, which in some countries like China is mainly a male activity, is a habit that contributes to increasing significantly the case fatality rates among men.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Sex-based immunological differences, lesser prevalence of smoking in women and men developing co-morbid conditions such as hypertension at a younger age than women could have contributed to the higher mortality in men.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In Europe as of February 2020, 57% of the infected people were men and 72% of those died with COVID‑19 were men.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Research has shown that viral illnesses like Ebola, HIV, influenza and SARS affect men and women differently.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In the US, a greater proportion of deaths due to COVID‑19 have occurred among African Americans and other minority groups.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Structural factors that prevent them from practising social distancing include their concentration in crowded substandard housing and in "essential" occupations such as retail grocery workers, public transit employees, health-care workers and custodial staff.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Greater prevalence of lacking health insurance and care of underlying conditions such as diabetes, hypertension, and heart disease also increase their risk of death.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Similar issues affect Native American and Latino communities.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On the one hand, in the Dominican Republic there is a clear example of both gender and ethnic inequality.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In this Latin American territory, there is great inequality and precariousness that especially affects Dominican women, with greater emphasis on those of Haitian descent.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to a US health policy non-profit, 34% of American Indian and Alaska Native People (AIAN) non-elderly adults are at risk of serious illness compared to 21% of white non-elderly adults.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The source attributes it to disproportionately high rates of many health conditions that may put them at higher risk as well as living conditions like lack of access to clean water.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Leaders have called for efforts to research and address the disparities.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In the UK, a greater proportion of deaths due to COVID‑19 have occurred in those of a Black, Asian, and other ethnic minority background.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] That structure imposes greater risks that those affected will develop a more severe form of the disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The findings are from Professor Svante Pääbo and researchers he leads at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology and the Karolinska Institutet.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] This admixture of modern human and Neanderthal genes is estimated to have occurred roughly between 50,000 and 60,000 years ago in Southern Europe.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Biological factors (immune response) and the general behaviour (habits) can strongly determine the consequences of COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Most of those who die of COVID‑19 have pre-existing (underlying) conditions, including hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to March data from the United States, 89% of those hospitalised had preexisting conditions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The Italian Istituto Superiore di Sanità reported that out of 8.8% of deaths where medical charts were available, 96.1% of people had at least one comorbidity with the average person having 3.4 diseases.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to this report the most common comorbidities are hypertension (66% of deaths), type 2 diabetes (29.8% of deaths), ischaemic heart disease (27.6% of deaths), atrial fibrillation (23.1% of deaths) and chronic renal failure (20.2% of deaths).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Most critical respiratory comorbidities according to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), are: moderate or severe asthma, pre-existing COPD, pulmonary fibrosis, and cystic fibrosis.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Evidence stemming from meta-analysis of several smaller research papers also suggests that smoking can be associated with worse outcomes.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] When someone with existing respiratory problems is infected with COVID‑19, they might be at greater risk for severe symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] COVID‑19 also poses a greater risk to people who misuse opioids and amphetamines, insofar as their drug use may have caused lung damage.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In August 2020, the CDC issued a caution that tuberculosis (TB) infections could increase the risk of severe illness or death.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The WHO recommended that people with respiratory symptoms be screened for both diseases, as testing positive for COVID‑19 could not rule out co-infections.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Some projections have estimated that reduced TB detection due to the pandemic could result in 6.3 million additional TB cases and 1.4 million TB-related deaths by 2025.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The virus is thought to be of natural animal origin, most likely through spillover infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A joint-study conducted in early 2021 by the People's Republic of China and the World Health Organization indicated that the virus descended from a coronavirus that infects wild bats, and likely spread to humans through an intermediary wildlife host.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There are several theories about where the index case originated and investigations into the origin of the pandemic are ongoing.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to articles published in July 2022 in *Science*, virus transmission into humans occurred through two spillover events in November 2019 and was likely due to live wildlife trade on the Huanan wet market in the city of Wuhan (Hubei, China).
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Doubts about the conclusions have mostly centered on the precise site of spillover.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Earlier phylogenetics estimated that SARS-CoV-2 arose in October or November 2019.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A phylogenetic algorithm analysis suggested that the virus may have been circulating in Guangdong before Wuhan.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Most scientists believe the virus spilled into human populations through natural zoonosis, similar to the SARS-CoV-1 and MERS-CoV outbreaks, and consistent with other pandemics in human history.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change several social and environmental factors including climate change, natural ecosystem destruction and wildlife trade increased the likelihood of such zoonotic spillover.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] One study made with the support of the European Union found climate change increased the likelihood of the pandemic by influencing distribution of bat species.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Available evidence suggests that the SARS-CoV-2 virus was originally harboured by bats, and spread to humans multiple times from infected wild animals at the Huanan Seafood Market in Wuhan in December 2019.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A minority of scientists and some members of the U.S intelligence community believe the virus may have been unintentionally leaked from a laboratory such as the Wuhan Institute of Virology.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The US intelligence community has mixed views on the issue, but overall agrees with the scientific consensus that the virus was not developed as a biological weapon and is unlikely to have been genetically engineered.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There is no evidence SARS-CoV-2 existed in any laboratory prior to the pandemic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The first confirmed human infections were in Wuhan.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A study of the first 41 cases of confirmed COVID‑19, published in January 2020 in *The Lancet*, reported the earliest date of onset of symptoms as 1 December 2019.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Official publications from the WHO reported the earliest onset of symptoms as 8 December 2019.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Human-to-human transmission was confirmed by the WHO and Chinese authorities by 20 January 2020.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] According to official Chinese sources, these were mostly linked to the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market, which also sold live animals.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In May 2020, George Gao, the director of the CDC, said animal samples collected from the seafood market had tested negative for the virus, indicating that the market was the site of an early superspreading event, but that it was not the site of the initial outbreak.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Traces of the virus have been found in wastewater samples that were collected in Milan and Turin, Italy, on 18 December 2019.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] By December 2019, the spread of infection was almost entirely driven by human-to-human transmission.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The number of COVID-19 cases in Hubei gradually increased, reaching 60 by 20 December, and at least 266 by 31 December.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 24 December, Wuhan Central Hospital sent a bronchoalveolar lavage fluid (BAL) sample from an unresolved clinical case to sequencing company Vision Medicals.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 27 and 28 December, Vision Medicals informed the Wuhan Central Hospital and the Chinese CDC of the results of the test, showing a new coronavirus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A pneumonia cluster of unknown cause was observed on 26 December and treated by the doctor Zhang Jixian in Hubei Provincial Hospital, who informed the Wuhan Jianghan CDC on 27 December.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 30 December, a test report addressed to Wuhan Central Hospital, from company CapitalBio Medlab, stated an erroneous positive result for SARS, causing a group of doctors at Wuhan Central Hospital to alert their colleagues and relevant hospital authorities of the result.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The Wuhan Municipal Health Commission issued a notice to various medical institutions on "the treatment of pneumonia of unknown cause" that same evening.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Eight of these doctors, including Li Wenliang (punished on 3 January), were later admonished by the police for spreading false rumours and another, Ai Fen, was reprimanded by her superiors for raising the alarm.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The Wuhan Municipal Health Commission made the first public announcement of a pneumonia outbreak of unknown cause on 31 December, confirming 27 cases – enough to trigger an investigation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] During the early stages of the outbreak, the number of cases doubled approximately every seven and a half days.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In early and mid-January 2020, the virus spread to other Chinese provinces, helped by the Chinese New Year migration and Wuhan being a transport hub and major rail interchange.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 20 January, China reported nearly 140 new cases in one day, including two people in Beijing and one in Shenzhen.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Later official data shows 6,174 people had already developed symptoms by then, and more may have been infected.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A report in *The Lancet* on 24 January indicated human transmission, strongly recommended personal protective equipment for health workers, and said testing for the virus was essential due to its "pandemic potential".
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] On 30 January, the WHO declared COVID-19 a Public Health Emergency of International Concern.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] By this time, the outbreak spread by a factor of 100 to 200 times.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Italy had its first confirmed cases on 31 January 2020, two tourists from China.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Italy overtook China as the country with the most deaths on 19 March 2020.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] By 26 March the United States had overtaken China and Italy with the highest number of confirmed cases in the world.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Research on coronavirus genomes indicates the majority of COVID-19 cases in New York came from European travellers, rather than directly from China or any other Asian country.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Retesting of prior samples found a person in France who had the virus on 27 December 2019, and a person in the United States who died from the disease on 6 February 2020.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] As of 1 October 2021, *Reuters* reported that it had estimated the worldwide total number of deaths due to COVID‑19 to have exceeded five million.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The Public Health Emergency of International Concern for COVID-19 ended on 5 May 2023.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] By this time, everyday life in most countries had returned to how it was before the pandemic.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] After the initial outbreak of COVID‑19, misinformation and disinformation regarding the origin, scale, prevention, treatment, and other aspects of the disease rapidly spread online.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Humans appear to be capable of spreading the virus to some other animals, a type of disease transmission referred to as zooanthroponosis.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Some pets, especially cats and ferrets, can catch this virus from infected humans.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Symptoms in cats include respiratory (such as a cough) and digestive symptoms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Cats can spread the virus to other cats, and may be able to spread the virus to humans, but cat-to-human transmission of SARS-CoV-2 has not been proven.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Compared to cats, dogs are less susceptible to this infection.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Behaviours which increase the risk of transmission include kissing, licking, and petting the animal.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Rabbits can also be infected with Covid-19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The virus does not appear to be able to infect pigs, ducks, or chickens at all.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Mice, rats, and rabbits are unlikely to be involved in spreading the virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Tigers and lions in zoos have become infected as a result of contact with infected humans.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] As expected, monkeys and great ape species such as orangutans can also be infected with the COVID‑19 virus.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Minks, which are in the same family as ferrets, have been infected.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Minks may be asymptomatic, and can also spread the virus to humans.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Multiple countries have identified infected animals in mink farms.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Denmark, a major producer of mink pelts, ordered the slaughter of all minks over fears of viral mutations, following an outbreak referred to as Cluster 5.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A vaccine for mink and other animals was being researched in 2021, though by 2025 it appeared that animals were effectively vaccinated, with the exception of polar bears.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] International research on vaccines and medicines in COVID‑19 is underway by government organisations, academic groups, and industry researchers.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There has been a great deal of COVID‑19 research, involving accelerated research processes and publishing shortcuts to meet the global demand.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] By the end of 2020, hundreds of clinical trials had been undertaken, with research happening on every continent except Antarctica.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] More than 200 possible treatment were tested in humans that first year.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Modelling research has been conducted with several objectives, including predictions of the dynamics of transmission, diagnosis and prognosis of infection, estimation of the impact of interventions, or allocation of resources.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Modelling studies are mostly based on compartmental models in epidemiology, estimating the number of infected people over time under given conditions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Repurposed antiviral drugs make up most of the research into COVID‑19 treatments.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Other candidates in trials include vasodilators, corticosteroids, immune therapies, lipoic acid, bevacizumab, and recombinant angiotensin-converting enzyme 2.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Research on the antimalarial drugs hydroxychloroquine and chloroquine showed that they were ineffective at best, and that they may reduce the antiviral activity of remdesivir.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In June, initial results from the randomised RECOVERY Trial in the United Kingdom showed that dexamethasone reduced mortality by one third for people who are critically ill on ventilators and one fifth for those receiving supplemental oxygen.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Because this is a well-tested and widely available treatment, it was welcomed by the WHO, which is in the process of updating treatment guidelines to include dexamethasone and other steroids.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Based on those preliminary results, dexamethasone treatment has been recommended by the NIH for peoples with COVID‑19 who are mechanically ventilated or who require supplemental oxygen but not in people with COVID‑19 who do not require supplemental oxygen.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In September 2020, the WHO released updated guidance on using corticosteroids for COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The WHO recommends systemic corticosteroids for the treatment of people with severe and critical COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The WHO suggests not to use corticosteroids in the treatment of people with non-severe COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The updated guidance was based on a meta-analysis of clinical trials of people critically ill with COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In November 2020, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) issued an emergency use authorisation for the investigational monoclonal antibody therapy bamlanivimab for the treatment of mild-to-moderate COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Bamlanivimab is authorised for people with positive results of direct SARS-CoV-2 viral testing who are twelve years of age and older weighing at least 40 kilograms (88 lb), and who are at high risk for progressing to severe COVID‑19 or hospitalisation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] This includes those who are 65 years of age or older, or who have chronic medical conditions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The authorised use includes treatment for those who are 65 years of age or older or who have certain chronic medical conditions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] In April 2021, the FDA revoked the emergency use authorisation (EUA) that allowed for the investigational monoclonal antibody therapy bamlanivimab, when administered alone, to be used for the treatment of mild-to-moderate COVID‑19 in adults and certain paediatric patients.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A cytokine storm can be a complication in the later stages of severe COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A cytokine storm is a potentially deadly immune reaction where a large amount of pro-inflammatory cytokines and chemokines are released too quickly.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] A cytokine storm can lead to ARDS and multiple organ failure.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Data collected from Jin Yin-tan Hospital in Wuhan, China indicates that people who had more severe responses to COVID‑19 had greater amounts of pro-inflammatory cytokines and chemokines in their system than people who had milder responses.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] These high levels of pro-inflammatory cytokines and chemokines indicate presence of a cytokine storm.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Tocilizumab has been included in treatment guidelines by China's National Health Commission after a small study was completed.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] It is undergoing a Phase II non-randomised trial at the national level in Italy after showing positive results in people with severe disease.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Combined with a serum ferritin blood test to identify a cytokine storm (also called cytokine storm syndrome, not to be confused with cytokine release syndrome), it is meant to counter such developments, which are thought to be the cause of death in some affected people.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There is no randomised, controlled evidence that tocilizumab is an efficacious treatment for CRS.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Prophylactic tocilizumab has been shown to increase serum IL-6 levels by saturating the IL-6R, driving IL-6 across the blood–brain barrier, and exacerbating neurotoxicity while having no effect on the incidence of CRS.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Lenzilumab, an anti-GM-CSF monoclonal antibody, is protective in murine models for CAR T cell-induced CRS and neurotoxicity and is a viable therapeutic option due to the observed increase of pathogenic GM-CSF secreting T cells in hospitalised patients with COVID‑19.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Transferring purified and concentrated antibodies produced by the immune systems of those who have recovered from COVID‑19 to people who need them is being investigated as a non-vaccine method of passive immunisation.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Viral neutralisation is the anticipated mechanism of action by which passive antibody therapy can mediate defence against SARS-CoV-2.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The spike protein of SARS-CoV-2 is the primary target for neutralising antibodies.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] As of 8 August 2020, eight neutralising antibodies targeting the spike protein of SARS-CoV-2 have entered clinical studies.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] It has been proposed that selection of broad-neutralising antibodies against SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-CoV might be useful for treating not only COVID‑19 but also future SARS-related CoV infections.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Other mechanisms, however, such as antibody-dependant cellular cytotoxicity or phagocytosis, may be possible.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Other forms of passive antibody therapy, for example, using manufactured monoclonal antibodies, are in development.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The use of passive antibodies to treat people with active COVID‑19 is also being studied.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] This involves the production of convalescent serum, which consists of the liquid portion of the blood from people who recovered from the infection and contains antibodies specific to this virus, which is then administered to active patients.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] This strategy was tried for SARS with inconclusive results.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] An updated Cochrane review in May 2023 found high certainty evidence that, for the treatment of people with moderate to severe COVID‑19, convalescent plasma did not reduce mortality or bring about symptom improvement.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] There continues to be uncertainty about the safety of convalescent plasma administration to people with COVID‑19 and differing outcomes measured in different studies limits their use in determining efficacy.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Since the outbreak of the COVID‑19 pandemic, scholars have explored the bioethics, normative economics, and political theories of healthcare policies related to the public health crisis.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] Academics have pointed to the moral distress of healthcare workers, ethics of distributing scarce healthcare resources such as ventilators, and the global justice of vaccine diplomacies.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/covid-19-p02] The socio-economic inequalities between genders, races, groups with disabilities, communities, regions, countries, and continents have also drawn attention in academia and the general public.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/insch-war-memorial-hospital] The hospital, which was built by public subscription to create a memorial for local people who gave their lives in the First World War, opened in August 1922.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/insch-war-memorial-hospital] It joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/insch-war-memorial-hospital] A day unit was added in 1972 and a further extension was opened in 1993.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/insch-war-memorial-hospital] The hospital has been closed since March 2020 as management claimed it could not be operated safely due to COVID-19 restrictions.
[src:insch-war-memorial-hospital/insch-war-memorial-hospital] The hospital's Minor Injury Unit Service is delivered by a dedicated Minor Injury trained nurse and operates Monday to Friday between 8am and 6pm.
